@Norvik_-ug3ge yeah Sarah Connor in The Terminator is strong.

She's just a normal young woman in a low paid job who enjoys going out clubbing and suddenly she's thrown into this unbelievable nightmare and she does two things almost unheard of with female characters in action movies these days.  Firstly she evolves.  Secondly she learns from a man.  By the end of the movie she's bandaging a wound, learning to make homemade explosives, yelling "On your feet soldier!" at Reese and ultimately she's the one who finally stops the Terminator.

We see how much further she's evolved and how much tougher she's become in T2, but she's not invulnerable or infallible.  Across those two movies Sarah Connor is an extremely well written character.

@jjc5407 Another sign of Sarah Connor being well-written is that in T2 she has her own fall and redemption. Right after recovering the weapons from the cache, she gouges "no fate" into the tabletop. i.e. humans have free will. Yet at that point she decides to assassinate Dyson, despite the fact that he hasn't yet invented the chip. She's pre-judging him on actions he may not necessarily do. We can see her point - if she murders Dyson, and it avoids the horrors to come, isn't that justified?
John Connor says it isn't. He pursues his mother, intending to stop her. Okay, hollywood bottles it and uses deus ex machina to prevent her succeeding rather than letting a male character correct a female one, but she does actually pull the trigger. John rescues his mother twice - her body from the institution, and her self from the demons of anger and revenge masquerading as righteousness.
I think its depressingly significant that in our times we hear a great deal about Sarah Connor's protective maternal instincts, but nothing about John Connor as the voice of his mother's conscience.
